    "result": "L",
    "boxscore_url": "https://www.gojacks.com/sports/baseball/stats/2026/oral-roberts/boxscore/14928",
    "recap_url": "https://www.gojacks.com/news/2026/3/13/baseball-sdsu-again-comes-up-one-run-short",
    "recap_headline": "South Dakota State University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "TULSA, Okla. \u2014 Oral Roberts broke a 2-all tie with a pair of runs in the bottom of the eighth inning and held off South Dakota State for a 4-3 victory in the Summit League baseball opener for both teams Friday night at Chapman Park.\nThe Golden Eagles improved to 8-9 overall, while SDSU dropped to 5-12 on the season.\nAfter Jackrabbit reliever\nDrew McDowell\nheld ORU off the board through his first four innings of work, the Golden Eagles were able to solve the SDSU right-hander in what would be their final at-bat. Wailele Kane-Yates opened the frame by being hit by a pitch and moved to second base on a successful sacrifice bunt by Cooper Kelly. Kane-Yates moved up another base on a base hit by Martell Davis and later scored the go-ahead run on a single to right field by Tyler Brodrick to end McDowell's outing.\nDavis would come across on a wild pitch for the second run of the inning.\nSDSU continued to battle as it received back-to-back singles from\nNate Wachter\nand\nDayton Franke\nto open the top of the ninth.\nCarter Taylor\nmoved both Wachter and pinch-runner\nLuke Evenson\ninto scoring position by dropping down a sacrifice bunt, with Wachter bringing the Jackrabbits back to within a run as he scored on a groundout off the bat of\nKeagen Jirschele\n. Evenson was left stranded at third as\nNic Werk\ngrounded out to end the game.\nEach of the Jackrabbits' first two runs were unearned. Werk singled to open the third, advanced to third on an error and scored on a groundout RBI by\nLuke Luskey\n. SDSU then tied the game at 2-all. Werk also scored in the fifth after a leadoff walk as he moved up bases on a passed ball, sacrifice bunt and sacrifice fly by\nNolan Grawe\n.\nORU grabbed its first lead of the night with two runs in the bottom of the third. Makani Tanaka hit a solo home run for the first Golden Eagle tally and Kelly added a run-scoring infield single later in the inning.\nMcDowell turned in his longest outing as a Jackrabbit with 4 1/3 innings of relief. He allowed four hits, struck out four and walked two.\nTy Madison\nworked the first 2 1/3 innings for SDSU, giving up two runs on three hits. He walked two and struck out two.\nGolden Eagle starter Easton Teel did not factor in the decision despite seven solid innings. The right-hander struck out four, walked one and gave up only two hits. Jack Hill pitched the final two innings and was credited with the win.\nORU held an 8-4 advantage in hits, led by Kane-Yates with a 2-for-3 night at the plate. Wachter posted two of the Jackrabbits' four hits.\nON DECK\nGame 2 of the series is slated for a 2 p.m. first pitch on Saturday.\nNOTES\nORU leads the all-time series, 84-23, and has won the last 10 meetings\nSDSU fell to 8-10 in Summit League openers since joining the league at the start of the 2008 season\nThe Jackrabbits dropped to 1-5 in one-run games this season, with five of their last six games decided by a single score\nSDSU center fielder\nOwen Siegert\nhad both his seven-game hitting streak and streak of 16 consecutive games reaching base safely come to an end\nWachter recorded his fourth multi-hit game of the season\nMcDowell's previous long outing was three innings last Friday against Northwestern, a relief appearance in which he allowed one unearned run\n-GoJacks.com-"
